commit 43fff1442000a2cac3d2b5afb47c24bf24a11c9c
Author: robobun <robobun@oven.sh>
Date:   Wed Jun 3 15:30:46 2026 -0700

    Fix panic converting over-long Windows paths to UTF-16 (#31694)
    
    Fixes a Windows crash reported via crash telemetry (BUN-39DM): `Panic:
    range end index 49151 out of range for slice of length 49150`, in
    `bun_paths::string_paths::to_kernel32_path` →
    `convert_utf8_to_utf16_in_buffer`, reached from `node:fs`
    (`PathLike::os_path_kernel32`).
    
    This is the same bug as #20258 (`fs.existsSync` crashing with `index out
    of bounds: index 49151, len 49151` for paths of 49151–98302 chars — the
    Zig-side manifestation of the identical overflow); its exact repro is
    included in the tests.
    
    Fixes #20258
    
    ### Repro
    
    On Windows, any `node:fs` call with an ASCII path between 32767 and
    98302 characters, e.g.:
    
    ```js
    fs.existsSync("C:\\" + "a".repeat(49200));        // panic (osPathKernel32)
    fs.mkdirSync("C:\\" + "a".repeat(40000));          // panic (WPathBuffer)
    ```
    
    Reproduced on Linux through the conversion itself (it's
    platform-independent slice math) with the Windows buffer shape:
    
    ```
    panic: convert_utf8_to_utf16_in_buffer: buf too small (have 49146 u16 for 49203 input bytes)
    ```
    
    (49146 = the 49151-u16 view of the 98302-byte `PathBuffer`, minus the
    `\\?\` prefix and NUL — the same arithmetic as the 49150/49151 in the
    crash report, which predates the assert.)
    
    ### Cause
    
    Path validation at the JS boundary (`Valid::path_string_length`) bounds
    the UTF-8 **byte** length against `MAX_PATH_BYTES` (98302 on Windows),
    but the converted path is written into fixed-size UTF-16 buffers:
    `WPathBuffer` holds 32767 units and `os_path_kernel32`'s u16 view of
    `PathBuffer` holds 49151. One UTF-16 unit can take up to 3 UTF-8 bytes,
    so the byte bound admits ASCII paths of up to 98302 units. simdutf's
    convert API takes only an output pointer — it writes however many units
    the input needs — so over-long input either trips the capacity assert or
    (in older builds) writes past the slice and panics slicing the result.
    The Zig original has the same latent bug (silent overflow); the port
    surfaced it.
    
    ### Fix
    
    - **`strings::fits_in_wide_path_buffer`** (`src/paths/string_paths.rs`):
    can the path's UTF-16 form — plus the longest converter prefix
    (`\??\UNC\`), a trailing slash, and the NUL — fit `PATH_MAX_WIDE`
    (32767) units? No path that fails this can exist on NT, so nothing valid
    is rejected. O(1) for normal paths; the simdutf (SIMD) UTF-16 length is
    only computed when the byte length exceeds the limit. On malformed bytes
    that length is an estimate, so such over-long input can pass the check —
    the bounds-checked conversion below stays the backstop and fails safe.
    - **`PathLike::slice_w` / `os_path` / `os_path_kernel32`**
    (`src/runtime/node/types.rs`) return `Result<_, NameTooLong>`, checking
    the normalized input before converting; call sites map it per-op the way
    the Zig-side fix for this crash (#27775) did: `exists` → `false` ("over
    PATH_MAX_WIDE — can't exist on disk"), recursive `mkdir` →
    `ENAMETOOLONG` with `syscall: "mkdir"`, `copyFile`/`cp` → `ENAMETOOLONG`
    with `syscall: "copyfile"`, each with the offending path attached.
    Rejecting at the conversion call sites rather than generically at the
    `PathLike` parse boundary keeps per-op error attribution — in particular
    `fs.watch`'s own over-long-path handling (`syscall: "watch"` from its
    cwd-join check) stays intact.
    - **`try_convert_utf8_to_utf16_in_buffer`**
    (`src/bun_core/string/immutable.rs`): checked conversion that never
    writes past the output buffer. simdutf is only entered when the output
    provably fits, and the WTF-8 fallback re-checks capacity per write —
    stray continuation bytes expand to one U+FFFD *each*, exceeding the
    simdutf length estimate, a hole the previous assert missed. The
    panicking `convert_utf8_to_utf16_in_buffer` now delegates to it,
    contract unchanged.
    - **`to_w_path_maybe_dir`** (`src/paths/string_paths.rs`, the chokepoint
    for all wide-path conversions) fails safe to an empty path for over-long
    input instead of overflowing, so internal non-`PathLike` callers
    (resolver, install, watcher, …) get a clean syscall error rather than a
    panic; same guard for the two copy-based normalizers. This mirrors the
    existing `slice_z_with_force_copy` handling of over-long POSIX paths.
    - **Rust unit tests** in `src/paths/string_paths.rs` exercising the
    Windows buffer shapes on every platform (`cargo test -p bun_paths`; they
    also run in the `rust:miri` CI lane — the simdutf externs are satisfied
    by pure-Rust scalar stubs in the test module since the C++
    implementation only exists in the full binary link).
    
    `Cargo.lock`: adds the `bstr` entry for `bun_bin` that is already
    declared in its `Cargo.toml` on main (any cargo invocation regenerates
    it).
    
    ### Verification
    
    Tests:
    
    - **All platforms**: `cargo test -p bun_paths` — exact-capacity fill,
    over-long ASCII and invalid WTF-8 failing safe to empty, multi-byte
    input longer in bytes than the buffer converting, kernel32 prefixing,
    the production crash shape (49151-u16 buffer → prefix-only fail-safe)
    and a just-under-the-limit conversion (guards against over-rejection),
    plus `fits_in_wide_path_buffer`'s bounds. Fails on the unfixed
    conversion: with the chokepoint guard reverted, the three over-long
    tests panic (`buf too small (have 49146 u16 for 49203 input bytes)`).
    - **Windows lane** (`test/js/node/fs/fs-path-length.test.ts`, which
    already covers the sibling `normalizePathWindows` hardening):
    `existsSync` returns `false` instead of crashing (including the exact
    #20258 boundary lengths 49150/49151/64503/98302/98303); recursive
    `mkdirSync`, `copyFileSync` (src and dest), `cpSync`,
    `fs.promises.mkdir`, and Buffer paths all throw `ENAMETOOLONG`; a
    multi-byte path long in bytes (90152) but within the UTF-16 bound (30152
    units, split into components under NTFS's 255-unit limit) keeps working.
    - `test/js/node/watch/fs.watch.test.ts` — the over-long relative path
    test that caught the first iteration's parse-boundary approach in CI —
    passes unchanged with the call-site design.
    
    `cargo check` passes for linux-gnu and windows-msvc targets; clippy
    clean on the four touched crates; `bun bd test
    test/js/node/fs/fs-path-length.test.ts`, `fs-mkdir.test.ts`,
    `glob/path-length.test.ts`, and `test/js/node/path/` all pass.
    
    ### CI status
    
    The previous build (59909) was green on everything this diff touches —
    all build lanes, all 16 Windows x64/x64-baseline test shards (the lanes
    that run the `fs-path-length.test.ts` Windows suite), and `cargo miri
    test` — with six red jobs all traced to runner problems (a streams
    chunk-coalescing timing flake on debian-13; broken Docker daemon, legacy
    Docker CLI, a Squid container, and a full MinIO disk on the macOS
    agents). Details in [the triage
    comment](https://github.com/oven-sh/bun/pull/31694#issuecomment-4602897745).
    A fresh build is running for the latest commit.

