commit bf79fe702c95f3424bd5a065ba956bc2fec8521f
Author: Jarred Sumner <jarred@jarredsumner.com>
Date:   Fri Jun 5 12:58:45 2026 -0700

    Replace phf maps with a length-dispatched comptime string map macro (#31875)
    
    ## What this does
    
    Replaces every `phf::Map` / `phf::Set` in the workspace with an in-tree
    `comptime_string_map!` / `comptime_string_set!` macro, converts the
    hand-rolled length-gated lookup tables that had previously forked off
    from phf for speed, and drops the workspace `phf` dependency (`phf
    0.11`, `phf_macros`, `phf_shared`, `phf_generator`, `siphasher`, and
    their `rand` subtree). A `phf 0.13` remains in `Cargo.lock` only as a
    transitive dependency of the vendored `lol_html` (via servo's
    `cssparser`/`selectors`); none of Bun's own code uses it.
    
    ## Why
    
    phf hashes every lookup at runtime: a SipHash13 round over the full key,
    a displacement-table probe, then a final slice compare — paid even on
    misses, which dominate for tables probed with arbitrary identifiers
    (lexer keyword/global tables). The codebase had already voted on this:
    several hot paths (`known_global.rs`, `Method::which`, the EVP lookups,
    easing keywords, lexer tables) had hand-written the same length-gated
    match to avoid phf, each with its own PERF comment. That left a
    declarative-but-slow option and a fast-but-verbose one; this PR makes
    the declarative form the fast form and unifies both populations on it.
    
    ## How lookups compile
    
    The macro groups keys by length at expansion time and emits `match
    key.len()` plus constant-length `==` compares, verified by assembly
    inspection on aarch64 and x86-64:
    
    - Length dispatch is a jump table / compare tree; the wrong length never
    touches key bytes.
    - Constant compares lower to word-sized loads against immediates (a
    6-byte bucket compiles to one 4-byte + one 2-byte load OR-combined, then
    a branchless compare tree across the bucket's keys). No hashing, no
    memcmp calls.
    - Keys longer than 64 bytes (LLVM's inline-expansion limit is 4×16-byte
    loads) emit branchless 8/4/2/1-byte XOR-accumulate chunks, which SLP
    lowers to 16-byte vector XOR/OR reductions. Measured on an 84-byte key:
    hit 3.79ns vs 4.32ns through memcmp; last-byte miss 3.24ns vs 6.80ns
    (memcmp only wins first-byte misses, and same-length MIME keys share
    long prefixes).
    - Hand-rolled nested byte-string *pattern matching* (`match name {
    b"Set" => … }`) lowers to byte-by-byte compare tries, so converting
    those sites is itself a small win.
    
    ## Key storage
    
    Lookups never read a key table — keys are compare-instruction immediates
    — so keys are stored only for the `entries()`/`keys()` iterators, as one
    concatenated blob plus a per-key length array (`u8`/`u16`/`u32`, sized
    to the longest key) rather than `(&'static [u8], V)` tuples.
    Consequences:
    
    - Zero load-time relocations: under phf (and a tuple-table port), every
    key pointer cost a rebase fixup plus 16 bytes of `__DATA,__const` —
    ~3.5k of the binary's ~88k fixups. All map data now lands in
    `__TEXT,__const`.
    - Maps that never iterate emit no key data at all (verified at the
    object level: the compiled `bun_http_types` rlib contains no pointer
    tables).
    - Tables are pure const data — no `Lazy`, no initializers, nothing at
    startup.
    - `ENTRIES`/`KEYS` remain as consts for const-eval consumers; a const
    only materializes a pointer table where referenced, so unused ones are
    free.
    
    ## What changed
    
    - New proc macro `src/bun_core_macros/comptime_string_map.rs`, plus the
    `ComptimeStringMap` trait, `macro_rules!` wrappers, and unit tests in
    `src/bun_core/comptime_string_map.rs`.
    - ~60 files converted from `phf_map!`/`phf_set!`. The generated API is
    deliberately phf-shaped (`get(&[u8]) -> Option<&'static V>`,
    `contains_key`, `entries`/`keys`/`values`), so most call sites are
    unchanged.
    - 24 files of hand-rolled tables converted (net −568 lines): HTTP method
    table, EVP algorithm names, known JS globals, JSX special props, lexer
    keyword wrappers (now delegating to the macro maps instead of
    duplicating them), QPACK header classification, h2 pseudo-header sets,
    redirect header-strip sets (exact compares instead of wyhash equality),
    encoding names, TOML keywords, valkey/postgres command words, easing
    keywords, strict-mode reserved words, install tag/host tables.
    Deliberately left alone: tables with per-entry `#[cfg]`
    (`DEFAULT_LOADERS`), prefix-plus-payload parses, per-arm side-effecting
    matches, and sub-4-key compares where a table buys nothing.
    - Generic helpers (`ComptimeStringMapExt::from_js`, `JSValue::to_enum*`,
    `strings::in_map_case_insensitive`) are generic over the trait instead
    of taking `&phf::Map`; call sites pass `&MAP` as before.
    - Maps that were associated consts move to module-level statics; the
    public `Type::MAP` path is preserved via a zero-sized handle const where
    external callers exist.
    - `src/codegen/bundle-modules.ts` emits the new macro for the generated
    `INTERNAL_MODULE_TAG` table.
    - Deleted `src/collections/comptime_string_map.rs` (a `Lazy`-based port
    with zero callers) and the per-crate `phf` manifest entries (~84
    `Cargo.toml`s); renamed the js_parser bench to `string_map_vs_hashmap`.
    
    ## Compile time
    
    Measured as release rebuilds of the crate (median of 3): the only delta
    vs main outside noise is `bun_http_types` (0.6s → ~2-3s; `-Ztime-passes`
    attributes it to LLVM passes on the 1184-entry MimeType compare body — a
    small parallel crate off the critical path). `bun_ast` and `bun_core`
    are within noise, debug builds are unchanged, and the phf crates leaving
    the graph offset the rest.
    
    ## How verified
    
    - `cargo check --workspace --keep-going`, `cargo check --tests` for
    bun_core/bun_ast/bun_http_types, `cargo clippy --workspace --no-deps` —
    all clean
    - `bun run rust:check-all` — 10/10 targets including FreeBSD and Windows
    (covers the cfg-gated per-OS errno maps)
    - Standalone proc-macro test harness
    (hit/miss/boundary/case-insensitive/iteration-order/sets/fn-pointer
    values, >64-byte keys mutated at first/middle/last byte) — all pass
    - `bun bd` debug build + smoke
    - Test files over the converted paths: fetch-redirect, bundler_loader,
    which, bun-cryptohasher, node-http2 — 713 tests, 0 failures
    
    ## Notes
    
    - `get()` returns `Option<&'static V>` exactly like phf, so `.copied()`
    / `*v` call sites did not change.
    - Maps keyed on `&'static str` now key on bytes; their lookups pass
    `name.as_bytes()`.
    - `entries()` / `keys()` yield `&'static [u8]` (phf yielded `&&'static
    [u8]`); the few iterator call sites were adjusted.
    - `get_ascii_case_insensitive` requires keys declared lowercase (same
    contract the phf-based `in_map_case_insensitive` had).
    - Duplicate keys remain a compile error, reported with a span on the
    offending key.

